title: Back Care and Manual Handling (Theory) - Revised
headline: Learn how to take much-needed precautions to prevent back injury during manual handling, with this free online course.
description: This free online back care and manual handling course will teach you the principles of safe lifting, how the back works, and precautions to take at home and at work that will prevent back injuries. Back injuries like sprains, strains, herniated discs, and fractured vertebrae can arise from accidents when lifting heavy loads and can be both painful and dangerous. Take this course today to prevent back injuries while lifting heavy loads.
courseDescription:
This course will first give you an overview of how your back works. You will learn about back injury and the causes of back pains. You will then study important legislation which covers Safety, Health, and Welfare at Work Act, the Manual Handling of Loads, as well as the Protection of Pregnant, Post-Natal, and Breastfeeding Employees. You will also learn the importance of a good back posture and suitable clothing for manual handling.

Next, you will learn about office ergonomics and the effects of incorrect body posture. You will also learn about manual handling ergonomics which aims to fit the task to the person rather than the person to the task. You will study the TILE model which includes Task,Individual Capability, Load, and Environment, and how it aims to help people to work within their capabilities and reduce the risk of injury. The course will also teach you the principles of safe lifting.

This course was developed by the National Federation of Voluntary Bodies, and is intended as a refresher training course for those who have previously completed a one day Manual Handling course. The course will teach you good back posture and important ergonomics that will prevent back pains. These are skills that can make a serious difference to your everyday life and comfort, so don't wait until it's too late! Check out the course now, and protect yourself against a serious future injury.

Start Course Now

  • Principles of Safe Lifting

  • The key points from this module are:
  • Manual handling is lifting, carrying, putting down, pushing, pulling, or supporting a load where there is risk of injury. A large proportion of back pain is thought to be attributable to manual handling injuries.

    Back injury can be CUMULATIVE: Injuries that occur overtime
    Back injury can be SUDDEN: Injuries can occur due to sudden unexpected/unplanned movements.

    Back muscles are not designed for lifting heavy loads, leg muscles power the lift. Strong abdominal muscles protect the lower back.

    Some causes of back pain include:
    • Poor posture
    • Slouching in front of the TV
    • Twisting while lifting a baby out of the car
    • Stooping to pick up objects from the floor
    • Carrying something that suddenly falls or moves causing a jerky motion
  • Different postures effect your spine. For example, unsafe loading on spine and its muscles increases with twisting or sitting down when handling a load.
